7095485a-9c09-4da4-881e-2493b25800b2	800d3a91-7011-449e-8089-d5b05e13d0d2	0	# Quantum Computing – Learning Snapshot\n\n> **Today I learned about quantum computing.**  \n> *Qubits can exist in superposition, meaning they represent both 0 and 1 simultaneously. This is fundamentally different from classical bits. The major challenge is decoherence.*\n\n---\n\n## 1. Key Concepts\n\n| Concept | What It Means | Why It Matters |\n|---------|---------------|----------------|\n| **Quantum bit (qubit)** | Basic unit of quantum information | Holds richer information than a classical bit |\n| **Superposition** | `|ψ⟩ = α|0⟩ + β|1⟩`, with `|α|² + |β|² = 1` | Enables parallelism; a single qubit can encode multiple states |\n| **Classical bit** | Binary state `{0, 1}` | Limit to a single definite value at any time |\n| **Decoherence** | Loss of quantum coherence due to interaction with the environment | Causes qubits to collapse to classical states, limiting computation time |\n\n---\n\n## 2. From Classical to Quantum\n\n- **Classical bits**: Deterministic, binary (0 or 1).  \n	[0.028062202,0.080247164,-0.16182691,-0.07885254,0.081604436,0.008097092,0.024319071,0.021340394,-0.008237242,-0.027087172,-0.054533597,0.043501075,0.024029562,0.020924967,-0.018748282,-0.029581917,-0.004203194,-0.010264225,0.04332593,0.026415471,-0.03450261,-0.010815179,-0.01623527,-0.01912135,0.03591775,0.024442688,-0.039859515,-0.048707634,-0.015616739,-0.00080335053,0.051521875,-0.07820726,0.00833141,-0.0033084091,-0.047440153,-0.06493861,-0.016206317,-0.00883805,0.050323088,-0.011715314,-0.010250741,-0.017993204,0.0056776935,-0.07826986,0.04136532,0.025765944,0.095274545,0.008728783,0.048621595,-0.0872733,0.043890473,-0.003474128,0.060732067,0.034314997,0.079686224,0.06787619,-0.024105156,-0.011558881,0.06523769,0.00039051592,0.053577263,0.02140571,-0.004232139,0.048062604,0.06352011,0.010409405,-0.020343233,0.05586254,-0.011857248,-0.034205843,0.062546805,-0.05002773,-0.008719664,0.066488095,0.0337698