ff342dd4-3052-42b0-ab66-edeebb34dbd1	1c77dc3b-b229-4bb8-97e2-c2d90385e4a0	0	# Feature Idea: Temporal Note Decay\n\nA simple yet powerful idea: give every note a *half‑life*. Instead of hard deletions, let relevance fade over time, but keep the ability to “reset” it on access. This mirrors how humans forget and rediscover information.\n\n---\n\n## 1. The Concept\n\n- **Temporal relevance**: Notes that are *not accessed* or *not linked to* gradually lose ranking weight in search results.\n- **Decay analogy**: Think of it as *radioactive decay* applied to knowledge.\n- **Reversibility**: A single access (read, edit, or link) resets the decay clock.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Why This Matters\n\n| Issue | Why a half‑life helps |\n|-------|----------------------|\n| **Information clutter** | Old meeting notes (e.g., 2019) no longer compete with fresh insights. |\n| **Search relevance** | Search rankings stay current, reflecting the most useful knowledge. |\n| **Human‑like memory** | Enables a natural forgetting mechanism that encourages users to revisit important content. |\n	[0.047203466,0.037317216,-0.17319125,-0.06584595,0.10461726,-0.011866794,0.026106387,0.023056353,0.052144583,-0.034134835,-0.014426065,0.038681954,0.0706551,0.0714874,0.023026843,-0.0024425231,-0.00042202033,-0.05542597,-0.01195087,0.056357756,0.013642781,-0.018892478,-0.043625902,-0.043436155,-0.035055384,0.060734306,-0.0058100205,-0.021745954,-0.032819998,0.062359747,0.04830619,-0.060464267,-0.0603612,0.00789122,-0.044930506,-0.033511307,0.047360547,0.036979176,0.0021397327,0.007986895,0.060408674,0.05824,0.023896875,-0.037016366,0.0825721,0.03588579,0.036126055,7.433416e-05,0.07109641,-0.084228486,0.016703818,-0.0064977882,0.042796798,0.012734414,0.0384974,0.021873474,0.030819207,-0.014716335,0.031006327,-0.012823338,0.075769275,0.031637747,-0.045074828,0.08936072,0.027560983,-0.021394026,-0.012436037,0.033660196,0.026724419,-0.048399728,0.03446076,0.026128171,-0.027293922,0.050804432,-0.03574539,0.03501964