09f16edd-d41d-469a-a41c-69232183080f	81b961d9-8881-483d-b7e6-e365bef92154	1	| **Caching Layer** | Considering **Valkey** (a Redis-compatible in‑memory data store) as an alternative to Redis for improved performance or feature set. |\n\n### REST vs. GraphQL (Detailed)\n\n- **REST**:  \n  - Multiple endpoints (`/users`, `/orders`, etc.).  \n  - Fixed response schemas; clients must issue multiple requests to gather related data.  \n  - Caching is typically done at the HTTP level (e.g., ETag, Cache‑Control).\n\n- **GraphQL**:  \n  - Single endpoint (`/graphql`).  \n  - Clients specify exactly which fields they need; reduces over‑fetching and under‑fetching.  \n  - Caching is more granular (e.g., query caching, persisted queries).\n\n### Caching Layer (Valkey vs. Redis)\n\n- **Redis** is a widely used key‑value store for caching.  \n- **Valkey** is an actively maintained fork of Redis that adds new features and performance improvements.  \n- Switching to Valkey can yield benefits such as:  \n  - Updated data structures (e.g., new hash map types).  \n	[0.01276121,0.077250645,-0.14758219,-0.04551812,0.07984248,-0.059500758,0.018550474,-0.0289957,-0.02972495,-0.05135726,0.0074505033,0.04277333,0.050888497,-0.023409083,-0.0052750986,-0.031627156,-0.011872465,-0.017856462,0.00035556787,0.05022481,-0.0529819,-0.009877771,0.016112303,-0.07245592,0.055594757,0.010056381,-0.0006466893,0.036388967,-0.017035117,0.055450734,0.016719827,-0.016477866,-0.0016511995,-0.003771798,-0.07140973,-0.023594445,0.014915624,0.022453818,0.021944067,-0.020943874,0.05008465,0.041482482,0.02529635,-0.047200527,0.01847841,-0.00032451368,0.013960779,0.0397154,0.10289192,-0.091779016,-0.011407933,0.050469685,0.019941794,0.009696016,0.09100607,0.05166978,0.0144889895,0.06273457,-0.022825828,-0.03158188,0.06769555,0.04508885,-0.015718335,0.0583727,0.04215336,-0.029431462,-0.036627434,0.026606062,0.020118747,-0.043616634,0.04732657,0.022735957,0.003727973,0.028776579,-0.032918535,-0.02420843,-0.03226028,-