e78d9545-a4e7-4748-9f1c-06fcffd9a729	f9844d30-23ba-4264-b957-a66a41e6b503	## Bluetooth Audio & GPU Thermal – Quick Fixes & Context\n\n### 1. Bluetooth audio drop‑outs  \n- **Problem**: Switching between headphones and speakers causes the audio stream to cut out.  \n- **Root cause**: *PipeWire* does not release the old sink fast enough when the audio device changes.  \n- **Work‑around**:  \n  ```bash\n  systemctl --user restart wireplumber\n  ```\n  – WirePlumber (the PipeWire session manager) re‑initialises the audio graph, clearing stale sink references.  \n\n**Related concepts**  \n- **PipeWire** – a unified multimedia framework that replaces PulseAudio for audio, handling Bluetooth profiles through *bluez-pipewire*.  \n- **Sink vs Source** – a *sink* consumes audio; when you unplug a device, PipeWire should drop the sink, but sometimes the reference lingers until WirePlumber restarts.\n\n### 2. RTX 3060 thermal behaviour  \n- **Observation**: Sustained load temperatures reach ~82 °C.  \n- **Recommendation**: Re‑apply thermal paste to improve heat transfer from GPU die to heatsink.  \n\n**Why 82 °C matters**  \n- NVIDIA recommends staying below 85 °C for prolonged operation.  \n- Re‑pastening can lower idle and load temperatures by 5–10 °C, extending component life and reducing fan noise.\n\n**Re‑pastening quick guide**  \n1. **Power down & disassemble** – remove GPU from the case, detach the cooling fan.  \n2. **Clean old paste** – use isopropyl alcohol and a lint‑free cloth.  \n3. **Apply new paste** – a pea‑size amount on the center of the GPU die.  \n4. **Re‑attach heatsink & fan** – secure with the original mounting screws.  \n5. **Re‑install GPU** – ensure thermal pad alignment, then power on.  \n\n**Further reading**  \n- NVIDIA’s *Thermal Management Guidelines* (https://docs.nvidia.com/gameworks/thermal/).  \n- PipeWire’s Bluetooth integration docs (https://pipewire.pages.freedesktop.org/pipewire/pipewire.html#bluetooth).\n\n---\n\n> **Key takeaways**  \n> - Restarting WirePlumber resolves transient Bluetooth sink issues caused by delayed release in PipeWire.  \n> - Monitoring GPU temperatures and addressing thermal paste degradation can prevent overheating during heavy workloads.  \n\nFeel free to reach out if you need deeper diagnostics or a step‑by‑step re‑pastening tutorial.	AI-enhanced revision with context	2026-01-12 19:54:53.178125-05	\N	\N
d51db9d7-e3fd-491a-80f4-2c55f8bac9eb	e1ee842f-6cfc-4af7-9b97-46fc580bd781	# Meeting Notes\n\n**Date:** 2024‑01‑10  \n**Participants:** Frontend & Backend teams\n\n---\n\n## 1. Discussion  \n- **API Endpoints for Frontend Integration** – The teams reviewed the current set of RESTful endpoints and how they map to the new UI components.  \n  - **Endpoint mapping**: `/users`, `/projects`, `/tasks`  \n  - **Data contract**: JSON schema for request/response payloads.  \n  - **Security**: JWT bearer token usage, CORS policy.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Action Items  \n\n| # | Task | Owner | Due |\n|---|------|-------|-----|\n| 1 | **Complete API testing** – Run full integration tests, covering success, edge cases, and error handling. | Backend QA | 2024‑01‑17 |\n| 2 | **Document all endpoints** – Create OpenAPI (Swagger) spec and generate interactive docs. | Backend Dev | 2024‑01‑19 |\n\n---\n\n## 3. Key Concepts  \n\n| Concept | Why it matters |\n|---------|----------------|\n| **API Endpoints** | The entry points through which the frontend communicates with the backend. |\n| **Frontend Integration** | Ensures UI components consume data correctly and handle responses consistently. |\n| **Testing** | Guarantees reliability, prevents regressions, and validates contract compliance. |\n| **Documentation** | Provides a single source of truth for developers and reduces onboarding time. |\n\n---\n\n## 4. Related Concepts (brief context)\n\n- **RESTful Design Principles** – Uniform interface, statelessness, cacheability.  \n- **OpenAPI Specification** – Structured definition of endpoints, parameters, and schemas; fuels tools like Swagger UI and Redoc.  \n- **Postman/Newman** – Useful for manual and automated API tests, can export collections for documentation.  \n- **JWT Authentication** – Secure token flow for stateless authentication; the frontend must include the token in the `Authorization` header.  \n- **CORS Configuration** – Needed to allow the frontend domain to access API resources from a different origin.  \n\nThese concepts support the action items and help maintain a robust, scalable API ecosystem.\n\n---\n\n## 5. Contextual Insights  \n\n- **Why Documentation is Crucial**  \n  Proper docs accelerate feature development and reduce the cognitive load on developers. When the API spec is versioned (e.g., `/v1/…`), the frontend can target a specific contract and plan migrations gracefully.\n\n- **Testing as a Continuous Practice**  \n  Automating API tests (e.g., with Jest or Postman/Newman) should be integrated into the CI pipeline. This prevents “integration hell” when new features touch shared endpoints.\n\n- **Security Considerations**  \n  Since the frontend relies on JWT, token expiry handling and refresh logic should be implemented early. Documenting the `refresh_token` flow will aid the mobile team later.\n\n---\n\n### Next Steps  \n\n- Backend will export the Postman collection after testing, and the team will convert it to an OpenAPI spec.  \n- Frontend will start consuming `/users` and `/projects` endpoints to verify the contract.  \n\nFeel free to add any clarifications or additional action items before our next sync.	AI-enhanced revision with context	2026-01-12 19:55:10.924584-05	\N	\N
