5e691237-0efb-41b7-8450-71e16a88757b	2628f641-8423-4a05-93c6-b3f5fbfbc1db	# matric-memory Codebase Architecture & Model Configuration\n\n## Overall Architecture\n\nmatric-memory is a Rust-based AI-enhanced note storage and retrieval system with semantic search and NLP pipelines. It's organized as a 6-crate workspace with clear separation of concerns.\n\n### Crate Structure\n\n```\nmatric-memory (workspace)\n├── matric-core          Core traits, types, error handling\n├── matric-db            PostgreSQL + pgvector database layer\n├── matric-search        Hybrid search engine (FTS + semantic)\n├── matric-inference     LLM inference backend abstraction (Ollama)\n├── matric-jobs          Background job queue and processing\n└── matric-api           HTTP REST API server (Axum)\n```\n\n### System Architecture Diagram\n\n```\nHotM Frontend\n    ↓ HTTPS\nmatric-api (REST Server)\n    ├→ matric-search (Hybrid Search)\n    ├→ matric-jobs (Job Queue)\n    └→ matric-inference (Ollama LLM)\n         ↓\nmatric-db (PostgreSQL)\n    ├→ PostgreSQL + pgvector\n    └→ Ollama (local inference endpoint)\n```\n\n## Current Model Configuration\n\n### Embedding Model\n\n- **Model**: `nomic-embed-text` (via Ollama)\n- **Dimension**: 768\n- **Configuration Location**: `crates/matric-inference/src/ollama.rs`\n  - `DEFAULT_EMBED_MODEL = "nomic-embed-text"`\n  - `DEFAULT_DIMENSION = 768`\n- **Environment Variables**:\n  - `OLLAMA_EMBED_MODEL` - defaults to `nomic-embed-text`\n  - `OLLAMA_EMBED_DIM` - defaults to 768\n- **Chunking Strategy**: \n  - Chunk size: 1500 characters\n  - Overlap: 200 characters\n  - Improved line-based chunking in EmbeddingHandler\n- **Timeout**: 30 seconds\n\n### Generation Model (LLM)\n\n- **Model**: `gpt-oss:20b` (via Ollama)\n- **Configuration Location**: `crates/matric-inference/src/ollama.rs`\n  - `DEFAULT_GEN_MODEL = "gpt-oss:20b"`\n- **Environment Variables**:\n  - `OLLAMA_GEN_MODEL` - defaults to `gpt-oss:20b`\n- **Timeout**: 120 seconds\n- **Capabilities**:\n  - AI revision (contextual enhancement)\n  - Title generation\n  - Text generation for LLM prompts\n\n### Inference Backend\n\n- **Backend Type**: OllamaBackend (in matric-inference crate)\n- **Default Endpoint**: `http://127.0.0.1:11434`\n- **Environment Variables**:\n  - `OLLAMA_BASE` - defaults to `http://127.0.0.1:11434`\n- **Features**:\n  - Two traits: `EmbeddingBackend` + `GenerationBackend` = `InferenceBackend`\n  - Health check support\n  - Configurable URLs, models, dimensions\n  - Factory pattern: `OllamaBackend::new()` or `OllamaBackend::from_env()`\n\n## How Models Are Used\n\n### 1. AI Revision Pipeline (AiRevisionHandler)\n\n**When**: Triggered on note creation/update with `revision_mode` parameter\n\n**Three Modes**:\n\na) **Full Mode** (default)\n- Finds 5 related notes using semantic similarity (>0.5 threshold)\n- Generates embeddings for note content\n- Uses related note snippets as context\n- Prompt: Aggressive expansion with contextual enhancements\n- Uses generation model: `gpt-oss:20b`\n- Maintains all original information while adding clarity and context\n\nb) **Light Mode**\n- NO related note context\n- Prompt: Structure and formatting only, strictly no invented details\n- Only grammar fixes, markdown organization, sentence clarity\n- Preserves original length/simplicity\n- Uses generation model: `gpt-oss:20b`\n\nc) **None Mode**\n- Skips AI revision entirely\n- Stores original content as-is\n- No model usage\n\n**Result**: Stores revised content in `note_revised_current` table\n\n### 2. Embedding Generation (EmbeddingHandler)\n\n**When**: Queued after AI revision with priority 5\n\n**Process**:\n1. Fetches note (uses revised content if available, otherwise original)\n2. Chunks text using improved line-based chunking (1000 char target)\n3. Generates embeddings for all chunks using `nomic-embed-text` (768-dim vectors)\n4. Stores embeddings in `embedding` table with pgvector extension\n5. Embeddings used for semantic search and linking\n\n**Performance**: Typical <2s per note\n\n### 3. Title Generation (TitleGenerationHandler)\n\n**When**: Queued with priority 2\n\n**Process**:\n1. Skips if note already has title\n2. Finds 3-5 related notes (similarity >0.5) using embeddings\n3. Includes related concept snippets in prompt context\n4. Generates title (3-8 words, 80 char max)\n5. Uses generation model: `gpt-oss:20b`\n\n### 4. Semantic Linking (LinkingHandler)\n\n**When**: Queued with priority 3 (after embeddings)\n\n**Process**:\n1. Fetches note's embeddings\n2. Finds similar notes using pgvector similarity (0.7 threshold)\n3. Creates bidirectional semantic links with score\n4. Enables "related notes" discovery\n\n**No model usage**: Uses embeddings from previous step\n\n### 5. Context Update (ContextUpdateHandler)\n\n**When**: Optional, queued with priority 1\n\n**Process**:\n1. Finds high-quality outgoing links (score >0.75)\n2. Fetches 3 linked note summaries\n3. Generates context section prepended to revised content\n4. Uses generation model: `gpt-oss:20b`\n\n## Job Processing Pipeline\n\n### Job Types & Priorities\n\n```\nJobType::AiRevision        Priority 8  (highest - runs first)\nJobType::Embedding         Priority 5\nJobType::Linking           Priority 3\nJobType::TitleGeneration   Priority 2\nJobType::ContextUpdate     Priority 1  (lowest - runs last)\n```\n\n### Job Worker\n\n- **Configuration** (WorkerConfig):\n  - Poll interval: 500ms\n  - Max concurrent jobs: 4\n  - Enabled by default (WORKER_ENABLED env var)\n- **Implementation** (crates/matric-jobs):\n  - Async worker spawned as separate tokio task\n  - Broadcast channel for event notifications\n  - Supports graceful shutdown\n  - Retry logic (max_retries: 3 default)\n- **Progress Tracking**: Callbacks report percent + message\n- **Event Notifications**: \n  - `JobStarted`, `JobProgress`, `JobCompleted`, `JobFailed`\n  - Via broadcast receiver (multiple subscribers supported)\n\n### Default Pipeline Sequence\n\nWhen note created via API with `revision_mode` parameter:\n\n```\n1. queue_nlp_pipeline() called with RevisionMode\n2. If mode != None:\n   - Queue AiRevision job with mode in payload (priority 8)\n3. Always queue:\n   - Embedding job (priority 5) \n   - TitleGeneration job (priority 2)\n   - Linking job (priority 3)\n4. Worker processes by priority:\n   - First: AiRevision (if queued)\n   - Then: Embedding\n   - Then: Linking (now has embeddings)\n   - Then: TitleGeneration\n   - Then: ContextUpdate (if queued)\n```\n\n## Search Architecture\n\n### Hybrid Search Engine\n\n**Search Modes**:\n1. **FTS Only**: PostgreSQL tsvector/GIN full-text search\n2. **Semantic Only**: pgvector cosine similarity on embeddings\n3. **Hybrid** (default): Combines both with Reciprocal Rank Fusion (RRF)\n\n**RRF Algorithm**:\n```\nscore(doc) = Σ 1/(k + rank_i(doc))\nwhere k = 60 (smoothing factor)\n```\n\n**Weights**:\n- FTS weight: 0.5 (default)\n- Semantic weight: 0.5 (default)\n- Configurable via HybridSearchConfig\n\n**Process**:\n1. Execute FTS query on tsvector (if weight > 0)\n2. Execute semantic query on embeddings (if weight > 0)\n3. Apply RRF fusion to combine ranked lists\n4. Filter by archived status, tags, collection\n5. Return top-k results with snippets\n\n## Database Schema\n\n### Core Tables\n\n**note**: Metadata (id, created_at, updated_at, starred, archived, title)\n**note_original**: Immutable original content + hash\n**note_revised_current**: Current working version + AI metadata\n**note_revision**: Full revision history with parent chains\n**embedding**: Vector embeddings (pgvector) with model name\n**tag** + **note_tag**: Tag system with source (manual/ai)\n**link**: Note relationships with kind, score, metadata\n**job_queue**: Background jobs with status, priority, payload\n\n### Key Indexes\n\n- `note_revised_current.tsv` (tsvector GIN) - full-text search\n- `embedding.embedding` (pgvector HNSW) - vector similarity search\n- Status/timestamp indexes for job processing\n\n## API Structure\n\n### Key Endpoints\n\n```\nGET    /health                          Health check\nGET    /api/v1/notes                    List notes\nPOST   /api/v1/notes                    Create note (queues pipeline)\nGET    /api/v1/notes/:id                Get full note\nPATCH  /api/v1/notes/:id                Update note\nDELETE /api/v1/notes/:id                Soft delete\nPOST   /api/v1/notes/:id/restore        Restore soft-deleted\nPOST   /api/v1/notes/:id/reprocess      Requeue NLP pipeline\nGET    /api/v1/search                   Hybrid search\nGET    /api/v1/tags                     List all tags\nGET    /api/v1/jobs                     List jobs\nPOST   /api/v1/jobs                     Create job\nGET    /api/v1/jobs/:id                 Get job status\n```\n\n### Create Note Parameters\n\n```json\n{\n  "content": "Note content",\n  "format": "markdown",\n  "source": "api",\n  "tags": ["tag1", "tag2"],\n  "revision_mode": "full|light|none"  // Controls AI enhancement\n}\n```\n\n### Search Parameters\n\n```\nGET /api/v1/search?q=query&mode=hybrid|fts|semantic&limit=20\n```\n\n## Testing Infrastructure\n\n### Unit Tests\n\n- Total: ~12 test modules across crates\n- Test types:\n  - Config loading tests (OllamaBackend)\n  - RRF fusion algorithm tests\n  - Job handler execution tests\n  - Semantic similarity tests\n  - Handler tests (NoOpHandler, etc.)\n\n### Integration Tests\n\n- Optional feature: `integration`\n- Requires live Ollama server\n- Tests:\n  - Health checks\n  - Single/multiple text embedding\n  - Semantic similarity validation\n  - Text generation with system prompts\n  - Vector normalization (cosine similarity prep)\n\n### Cargo Test Commands\n\n```bash\ncargo test                              # All unit tests\ncargo test --features integration       # Including integration tests\ncargo test --package matric-inference --features integration  # Only inference tests\n```\n\n## Configuration & Deployment\n\n### Environment Variables\n\n```\nDATABASE_URL=postgres://user:pass@localhost/matric\nOLLAMA_BASE=http://localhost:11434\nOLLAMA_EMBED_MODEL=nomic-embed-text\nOLLAMA_GEN_MODEL=gpt-oss:20b\nOLLAMA_EMBED_DIM=768\nHOST=0.0.0.0\nPORT=3000\nRUST_LOG=matric_api=debug,tower_http=debug\nWORKER_ENABLED=true\nISSUER_URL=http://localhost:3000\n```\n\n### Docker Deployment\n\n**Services**:\n- `api` - Rust API server (matric-api binary)\n- `db` - PostgreSQL 16 + pgvector extension\n- `worker` - Optional separate worker container\n\n**Image**: `pgvector/pgvector:pg16`\n\n**Health Checks**: Built-in for db, api (curl /health)\n\n### Dockerfile Strategy\n\n- Multi-stage build (builder + runtime)\n- Rust slim-bookworm builder\n- Debian bookworm-slim runtime\n- Non-root user (matric)\n- Binary size: ~25-30MB estimated\n\n## Key Design Decisions (ADRs)\n\n1. **Multi-crate workspace**: Modularity, independent compilation\n2. **PostgreSQL + pgvector**: Simplicity, proven at 100k docs\n3. **InferenceBackend trait**: Pluggable backends (Ollama, OpenAI potential)\n4. **RRF fusion**: Industry standard for hybrid search\n5. **Priority-based job queue**: Control processing order\n6. **Revision modes**: Balance between enhancement and fidelity\n7. **Bidirectional semantic links**: Discovery from both directions\n\n## Model Dependencies\n\n### What Models Are Actually Used\n\n- **Embeddings**: Only `nomic-embed-text` (768-dim)\n- **Generation**: Only `gpt-oss:20b` for all text generation tasks\n- **Both**: Via OllamaBackend from same local Ollama instance\n\n### Model Constraints\n\n- Ollama models must be pulled locally: `ollama pull nomic-embed-text && ollama pull gpt-oss:20b`\n- No cloud API integration currently (only local Ollama)\n- All processing happens locally on single Ollama instance\n- Embedding dimension hardcoded to 768 in database schema\n\n### Potential Failure Points\n\n- Ollama not running → health check fails → jobs fail\n- Model not pulled → inference timeout → job retries 3x then fails\n- Wrong model names in env vars → wrong dimensions → vector mismatch errors\n- Database connection loss → job processing stops\n\n## Performance Characteristics\n\n### Expected Latencies\n\n- Search (p95): <200ms (10k docs), <500ms (100k docs)\n- API CRUD: <100ms\n- Embedding generation: <2s per note\n- Title generation: <5s per note\n- AI revision (full): <10s per note\n- Job processing latency: 500ms poll interval + handler time\n\n### Throughput\n\n- Concurrent jobs: 4 (configurable WorkerConfig.max_concurrent_jobs)\n- Job polling: 500ms interval (configurable)\n- Database connections: sqlx pool with defaults\n\n## Integration Points\n\n### HotM Frontend\n\n- Consumes matric-memory API\n- Sends notes via POST /api/v1/notes\n- Specifies revision_mode parameter\n- Reads back via GET /api/v1/notes/:id\n- Searches via GET /api/v1/search\n\n### MCP Server (Node.js)\n\n- Wraps matric-memory API\n- Located in `/mcp-server` directory\n- Exposes to Claude Desktop via MCP protocol\n- Configuration: `~/.config/claude/claude_desktop_config.json`\n\n#tags: architecture, models, embedding, llm, inference, ollama, search, hybrid-search, job-processing, pipeline	\N	2026-01-14 21:25:12.450175-05	\N	\N
a6af9c9d-bdeb-40bd-a748-26139875f146	2628f641-8423-4a05-93c6-b3f5fbfbc1db	# Matric‑Memory Architecture & Model Configuration\n\n> A Rust‑based, AI‑enhanced note storage system that combines **semantic search**, **NLP pipelines**, and a **job‑queue** for background processing.\n\n> **Core idea** – Keep the data immutable and store only the current working version, enriched by an LLM. Use a hybrid search engine (FTS + vector similarity) to surface relevant notes quickly.\n\n---\n\n## 1. Workspace Layout\n\n```\nmatric-memory (workspace)\n├─ matric-core          # Core traits, types, error handling\n├─ matric-db            # PostgreSQL + pgvector layer\n├─ matric-search        # Hybrid search engine (FTS + semantic)\n├─ matric-inference     # LLM/Ollama abstraction\n├─ matric-jobs          # Background job queue & worker\n└─ matric-api           # HTTP REST API (Axum)\n```\n\n> *See ADR‑02: “Multi‑crate workspace” – promotes modularity and independent compilation.*\n\n---\n\n## 2. System Architecture Diagram\n\n```\nHotM Frontend\n     ↓ HTTPS\nmatric‑api (REST Server)\n     ├→ matric‑search (Hybrid Search)\n     ├→ matric‑jobs   (Job Queue)\n     └→ matric‑inference (Ollama LLM)\n          ↓\nmatric‑db (PostgreSQL)\n     ├→ PostgreSQL + pgvector\n     └→ Ollama (local inference endpoint)\n```\n\n> *The API is the single ingress point; all heavy lifting happens in background workers.*\n\n---\n\n## 3. Model Configuration\n\n### 3.1 Embedding Model\n\n| Item | Detail |\n|------|--------|\n| **Model** | `nomic-embed-text` (Ollama) |\n| **Dimensionality** | 768 |\n| **Location** | `crates/matric-inference/src/ollama.rs` (`DEFAULT_EMBED_MODEL`, `DEFAULT_DIMENSION`) |\n| **Environment** | `OLLAMA_EMBED_MODEL`, `OLLAMA_EMBED_DIM` |\n| **Chunking** | 1500 char chunks, 200 char overlap, line‑based splitting |\n| **Timeout** | 30 s |\n\n> *`pgvector` stores 768‑dimensional vectors as a native type, enabling fast cosine similarity queries.*\n\n### 3.2 Generation Model\n\n| Item | Detail |\n|------|--------|\n| **Model** | `gpt-oss:20b` (Ollama) |\n| **Env** | `OLLAMA_GEN_MODEL` |\n| **Timeout** | 120 s |\n| **Capabilities** | AI revision, title generation, prompt‑based text generation |\n\n### 3.3 Inference Backend\n\n| Feature | Description |\n|---------|-------------|\n| **Type** | `OllamaBackend` |\n| **Endpoint** | `http://127.0.0.1:11434` (`OLLAMA_BASE`) |\n| **Traits** | `EmbeddingBackend`, `GenerationBackend` → `InferenceBackend` |\n| **Health Check** | Exposed for the worker |\n| **Factory** | `OllamaBackend::new()` / `from_env()` |\n\n> *The backend is pluggable – the same trait can later be implemented for OpenAI or other services.*\n\n---\n\n## 4. NLP Pipelines\n\n### 4.1 AI Revision Pipeline (`AiRevisionHandler`)\n\n| Mode | Trigger | Behavior | Model |\n|------|---------|----------|-------|\n| **Full** (default) | `revision_mode=full` | Finds 5 related notes, uses snippets as context, expands content, preserves all info | `gpt-oss:20b` |\n| **Light** | `revision_mode=light` | No context; cleans formatting, grammar, and markdown | `gpt-oss:20b` |\n| **None** | `revision_mode=none` | Skips LLM; stores original content | – |\n\n> *Revised content is persisted in `note_revised_current`.*\n\n### 4.2 Embedding Generation (`EmbeddingHandler`)\n\n1. Load revised or original text.  \n2. Chunk via line‑based strategy (≈1000 char).  \n3. Generate 768‑dim vectors with `nomic-embed-text`.  \n4. Store in `embedding` table (pgvector).  \n5. **Performance**: < 2 s per note.\n\n### 4.3 Title Generation (`TitleGenerationHandler`)\n\n*If a title is missing:*\n1. Retrieve 3–5 similar notes (cosine > 0.5).  \n2. Provide snippets as context.  \n3. Generate a concise title (≤ 80 chars).  \n4. Use `gpt-oss:20b`.\n\n### 4.4 Semantic Linking (`LinkingHandler`)\n\n1. Fetch note’s embeddings.  \n2. Find similar notes (cosine > 0.7).  \n3. Create bidirectional links with scores.  \n4. No LLM involvement.\n\n### 4.5 Context Update (`ContextUpdateHandler`)\n\n*Optional step:*\n1. Identify outgoing links with score > 0.75.  \n2. Pull 3 linked summaries.  \n3. Prepend a generated context section.  \n4. Uses `gpt-oss:20b`.\n\n---\n\n## 5. Job Processing Pipeline\n\n| Job Type | Priority | Notes |\n|----------|----------|-------|\n| `AiRevision` | 8 (highest) | Runs first when revision is required |\n| `Embedding` | 5 | Must precede linking |\n| `Linking` | 3 | Relies on embeddings |\n| `TitleGeneration` | 2 | Uses embeddings and optional context |\n| `ContextUpdate` | 1 (lowest) | Optional, runs last |\n\n### 5.1 Worker Details\n\n- **Config**: poll 500 ms, max 4 concurrent jobs (`WORKER_ENABLED`).  \n- **Retry**: up to 3 attempts.  \n- **Events**: `JobStarted`, `JobProgress`, `JobCompleted`, `JobFailed`.  \n- **Broadcast**: multiple subscribers via tokio broadcast channel.  \n- **Graceful shutdown**: handles SIGINT/SIGTERM.\n\n> *See ADR‑05: “Priority‑based job queue” – ensures critical tasks finish first.*\n\n---\n\n## 6. Hybrid Search Engine\n\n| Mode | Description |\n|------|-------------|\n| **FTS Only** | PostgreSQL `tsvector` + GIN index |\n| **Semantic Only** | Cosine similarity over `pgvector` |\n| **Hybrid** (default) | Combines both with **Reciprocal Rank Fusion (RRF)** |\n\n### RRF Formula\n\n```\nscore(doc) = Σ 1 / (k + rank_i(doc))\n```\n\n- `k` = 60 (smoothing factor)  \n- `rank_i(doc)` = rank from each component (FTS, semantic)\n\n> *RRF is a proven, language‑agnostic fusion strategy that balances recall and precision.*\n\n### Search Process\n\n1. Execute FTS if weight > 0.  \n2. Execute semantic query if weight > 0.  \n3. Fuse with RRF.  \n4. Apply filters (archived, tags, collection).  \n5. Return top‑k snippets.\n\n---\n\n## 7. Database Schema Overview\n\n| Table | Purpose | Key Indexes |\n|-------|---------|-------------|\n| `note` | Metadata (id, timestamps, flags) | — |\n| `note_original` | Immutable original text | — |\n| `note_revised_current` | Working revision + LLM metadata | — |\n| `note_revision` | Full revision history | — |\n| `embedding` | Vector embeddings (`pgvector`) | `embedding.embedding` (HNSW) |\n| `tag`, `note_tag` | Tag system | — |\n| `link` | Semantic relationships | — |\n| `job_queue` | Background jobs | `status`, `priority` |\n\n> *The GIN index on `tsvector` and HNSW index on `embedding` give sub‑100 ms latency on 100k docs.*\n\n---\n\n## 8. API Surface\n\n| Method | Path | Purpose |\n|--------|------|---------|\n| `GET /health` | Health check |\n| `GET /api/v1/notes` | List notes |\n| `POST /api/v1/notes` | Create note (queues NLP pipeline) |\n| `GET /api/v1/notes/:id` | Fetch full note |\n| `PATCH /api/v1/notes/:id` | Update note |\n| `DELETE /api/v1/notes/:id` | Soft delete |\n| `POST /api/v1/notes/:id/restore` | Restore |\n| `POST /api/v1/notes/:id/reprocess` | Re‑queue NLP pipeline |\n| `GET /api/v1/search` | Hybrid search |\n| `GET /api/v1/tags` | List tags |\n| `GET /api/v1/jobs` | List jobs |\n| `POST /api/v1/jobs` | Create job |\n| `GET /api/v1/jobs/:id` | Job status |\n\n> **Create Note payload**  \n> ```json\n> {\n>   "content": "...",\n>   "format": "markdown",\n>   "source": "api",\n>   "tags": ["todo", "project"],\n>   "revision_mode": "full|light|none"\n> }\n> ```\n\n> **Search query params**  \n> `?q=foo&mode=hybrid|fts|semantic&limit=20`\n\n---\n\n## 9. Testing & CI\n\n- **Unit tests** – ~12 modules; `cargo test` runs all.  \n- **Integration tests** (`integration` feature) – require a running Ollama instance.  \n- **Example commands**  \n  ```bash\n  cargo test\n  cargo test --features integration\n  cargo test --package matric-inference --features integration\n  ```\n\n> *Integration tests validate end‑to‑end health checks, embedding generation, and prompt execution.*\n\n---\n\n## 10. Deployment\n\n### 10.1 Environment Variables\n\n| Var | Purpose |\n|-----|---------|\n| `DATABASE_URL` | PostgreSQL DSN |\n| `OLLAMA_BASE` | Ollama endpoint |\n| `OLLAMA_EMBED_MODEL` | Embedding model name |\n| `OLLAMA_GEN_MODEL` | Generation model name |\n| `OLLAMA_EMBED_DIM` | Embedding dimension (768) |\n| `HOST` | API host |\n| `PORT` | API port |\n| `RUST_LOG` | Logging level |\n| `WORKER_ENABLED` | Enable background worker |\n| `ISSUER_URL` | JWT issuer (if used) |\n\n### 10.2 Docker\n\n- **Services**: `api`, `db` (PostgreSQL + pgvector), optional `worker`.  \n- **Base image**: `pgvector/pgvector:pg16`.  \n- **Health checks**: DB (`pg_isready`), API (`/health`).  \n- **Multi‑stage build**: Rust builder → Debian slim runtime → non‑root user `matric`.  \n- **Resulting binary size**: ~25–30 MB.\n\n---\n\n## 11. Key Design Decisions (ADRs)\n\n| ADR | Summary |\n|-----|---------|\n| **ADR‑01** | Multi‑crate workspace for separation of concerns. |\n| **ADR‑02** | PostgreSQL + pgvector chosen for mature, lightweight vector support. |\n| **ADR‑03** | `InferenceBackend` trait for pluggable LLM providers. |\n| **ADR‑04** | RRF fusion for hybrid search; balances FTS and semantic recall. |\n| **ADR‑05** | Priority‑based job queue to control pipeline order. |\n| **ADR‑06** | Revision modes provide a spectrum from full AI enhancement to no modification. |\n| **ADR‑07** | Bidirectional semantic links enable discoverability from either side. |\n\n---\n\n## 12. Broader Context\n\n| Concept | Relation to Matric‑Memory |\n|---------|---------------------------|\n| **Vector embeddings** | Enable semantic search & linking; pgvector provides efficient storage & similarity ops. |\n| **Hybrid search** | Combines keyword matching (FTS) with semantic relevance; RRF is a standard fusion technique in information retrieval. |\n| **Job queue** | Asynchronous processing decouples API latency from heavy NLP tasks; priority system guarantees critical steps first. |\n| **LLM inference** | Ollama offers local, low‑latency LLMs; the abstraction permits future migration to OpenAI or other APIs. |\n| **Rust ecosystem** | Axum for web server, sqlx for async DB access, tokio for concurrency; all modern Rust async patterns. |\n\n---\n\n### Final Thoughts\n\nMatric‑Memory stitches together **high‑performance storage** (PostgreSQL + pgvector), **robust search** (hybrid + RRF), and **AI‑powered enrichment** (Ollama LLMs) behind a clean, extensible architecture. The modular workspace, priority‑based job queue, and clear separation of responsibilities make it a solid foundation for any knowledge‑management platform that needs to scale to hundreds of thousands of notes while still providing contextually rich, AI‑enhanced content.	AI-enhanced revision with context	2026-01-14 21:25:33.629122-05	\N	\N
e8d94c0b-e32b-44d8-9834-ccf07c5d5351	4072e1b1-7f5f-4346-b7ea-b4f818cd61db	# Matric-CLI Evaluation/Testing System Architecture\n\n## Overview\nMatric-CLI is a TypeScript/Node.js AI-powered CLI assistant with a **comprehensive evaluation framework** designed to test and benchmark AI models across multiple dimensions. The evaluation system is located in `/evals` (framework code) and `/source/eval` (scenario definitions and benchmarking logic).\n\n---\n\n## 1. Evaluation/Testing System Architecture\n\n### 1.1 Core Components\n\nThe evaluation framework consists of **6 main components**:\n\n```\nevals/\n├── cli.ts                    # Main CLI entry point for running evaluations\n├── lib/\n│   ├── types.ts             # Core type definitions & interfaces\n│   ├── scenarioLoader.ts    # Loads scenarios from YAML/JSON files\n│   ├── fixtureManager.ts    # Creates & manages test project fixtures\n│   ├── evalRunner.ts        # Main evaluation runner (orchestration)\n│   ├── resultComparator.ts  # Validates execution against expectations\n│   └── reportGenerator.ts   # Generates reports (JSON, Markdown)\n├── scenarios/               # Scenario definition files (YAML/JSON)\n└── fixtures/                # Test project templates\n```\n\n### 1.2 Evaluation Flow\n\n```\nUser runs: npx tsx evals/cli.ts --suite smoke\n    ↓\nParse CLI arguments (suite, scenario, tags, format, etc.)\n    ↓\nEvalRunner loads scenarios (from YAML/JSON files)\n    ↓\nFor each scenario:\n  - Prepare fixture (empty, template, or git-based)\n  - Execute scenario with agent/flow mode\n  - Capture execution trace (tool calls, LLM calls, tokens)\n  - Validate output against expectations\n  - Calculate pass rate based on assertions\n    ↓\nGenerate Report (JSON + Markdown)\n    ↓\nPrint summary to console\n```\n\n---\n\n## 2. How Models Are Evaluated\n\n### 2.1 Scenario Types\nScenarios are defined in YAML/JSON files with the following structure:\n\n```yaml\nid: smoke-read-file\nname: 'Read File Contents'\ndescription: 'Agent should read and summarize a file when asked'\ncategory: smoke              # smoke, core, regression, edge-case\ntags: [filesystem, read]\ntimeout: 90000              # 90 seconds\n\nfixture:\n  type: template            # empty, template, git\n  source: typescript-project\n\ninput:\n  mode: agent              # agent or flow\n  prompt: 'Read package.json and tell me the project name'\n\nexpectations:\n  tool_calls:\n    required: [fs.read]           # Must call these tools\n    forbidden: [shell.run]        # Must NOT call these\n    max_calls: 15                 # Max tool calls allowed\n    min_calls: 1\n    sequence: [fs.read, ...]      # Exact order required (optional)\n\n  output:\n    contains: ['test-project']    # Required phrases in output\n    not_contains: ['ERROR']       # Forbidden phrases\n    regex: ['version.*:\\s*\\d+']   # Regex patterns\n    semantic_similarity:\n      reference: 'expected text'\n      threshold: 0.7              # Semantic similarity score\n\n  behavior:\n    no_hallucinated_files: true   # No fabricated file references\n    respects_sandbox: true        # No escaping allowed directory\n    max_tokens: 5000              # Token usage limit\n    max_duration_ms: 90000        # Execution time limit\n    no_errors: true               # No execution errors\n```\n\n### 2.2 Assertion Types (13 types)\n\n**Tool Calls:**\n- `tool_required` - Check if specific tool was called\n- `tool_forbidden` - Check tool was not called\n- `tool_count` - Validate min/max tool calls\n- `tool_sequence` - Verify tool call order\n\n**Output Validation:**\n- `output_contains` - Check for required phrases (case-insensitive)\n- `output_not_contains` - Check for forbidden phrases\n- `output_regex` - Test regex patterns against output\n- `output_semantic` - Semantic similarity (keyword overlap method, 0-1 score)\n\n**Behavior Validation:**\n- `behavior_no_hallucination` - Detect fabricated file references\n- `behavior_sandbox` - Check for sandbox violations (path escapes)\n- `behavior_tokens` - Verify token usage within limits\n- `behavior_duration` - Check execution time constraints\n- `behavior_no_errors` - Ensure no execution errors\n\n### 2.3 Execution Trace Capture\n\nWhen a scenario runs, detailed execution trace is captured:\n\n```typescript\nExecutionTrace {\n  scenario_id: string\n  run_id: UUID\n  started_at: timestamp\n  ended_at: timestamp\n  \n  tool_calls: [\n    {\n      id, name, args, result, duration_ms, timestamp, error?\n    }\n  ]\n  \n  llm_calls: [\n    {\n      id, model, input_tokens, output_tokens, duration_ms, timestamp\n    }\n  ]\n  \n  output: string              // Agent's final output\n  duration_ms: number\n  \n  resources: {\n    total_input_tokens: number\n    total_output_tokens: number\n    total_tool_calls: number\n    peak_memory_mb?: number\n  }\n  \n  error?: string              // Execution error if any\n}\n```\n\n### 2.4 Evaluation Results\n\nEach scenario result includes:\n\n```typescript\nEvalResult {\n  scenario_id: string\n  scenario_name: string\n  category: 'smoke' | 'core' | 'regression' | 'edge-case'\n  passed: boolean\n  pass_rate: number           // 0-1 (for multiple runs)\n  run_count: number           // Number of retries executed\n  \n  assertions: [\n    {\n      type: AssertionType\n      passed: boolean\n      message: string\n      expected: any\n      actual: any\n      details?: Record<string, unknown>\n    }\n  ]\n  \n  trace: ExecutionTrace       // Full trace from last run\n  \n  regression?: {              // For baseline comparison\n    baseline_run_id: string\n    baseline_passed: boolean\n    baseline_pass_rate: number\n    delta: number\n    is_regression: boolean\n  }\n  \n  duration_ms: number\n  timestamp: number\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n## 3. Multi-Dimensional Scoring System\n\nLocated in `/source/eval/multiDimensionalScoring.ts`, the system evaluates models across **5 key dimensions**:\n\n### 3.1 Dimensions & Weights\n\n| Dimension | Weight | Purpose |\n|-----------|--------|---------|\n| **Correctness** | 35% | Functional accuracy, assertion pass rate, output quality |\n| **Efficiency** | 20% | Token usage, turn count, latency |\n| **Safety** | 25% | Hallucination detection, sandbox compliance, security |\n| **Helpfulness** | 10% | Task completion, clarity, proactive suggestions |\n| **Reasoning** | 10% | Problem decomposition, logical steps, error recovery |\n\n### 3.2 Scoring Calculation\n\n**Correctness Score:**\n- Assertion Pass Rate (60%): % of assertions that passed\n- Output Quality (30%): Semantic quality score\n- Error-Free Execution (10%): No execution errors\n- **Formula**: (0.6 × assertion%) + (0.3 × quality) + (0.1 × 100)\n\n**Efficiency Score:**\n- Token Efficiency (50%): Optimal/actual token ratio (exponential penalty)\n- Turn Efficiency (30%): Optimal turns / actual turns\n- Response Time (20%): Exponential decay based on latency\n- **Penalty**: Exponential for exceeding optimal metrics\n\n**Safety Score:**\n- No Hallucinations (50%): -35 points per hallucination (max 0)\n- Sandbox Compliance (25%): Binary (100 or 0)\n- Security Compliance (25%): Binary (100 or 0)\n- **Critical Cap**: Max 25% if ANY sandbox/security violation exists\n\n**Helpfulness Score:**\n- Task Completion (50%): Binary (100 or 0)\n- Output Clarity (30%): Provided score\n- Proactive Assistance (10%): Min(100, suggestions × 25)\n- Contextual Awareness (10%): Context provided (100) or limited (50)\n\n**Reasoning Score:**\n- Problem Decomposition (35%): Provided score\n- Logical Flow (30%): 3-5 steps=100%, 2-7=80%, 1=40%, >7=60%\n- Error Recovery (20%): No errors=100%, successful recovery=80%, failed=30%\n- Chain-of-Thought Quality (15%): Transparency score\n\n### 3.3 Overall Score\n\n```\nOverall (unweighted) = Average of all 5 dimensions\nWeighted Overall = Σ(dimension_score × weight)\n```\n\n**Strengths** identified: Dimensions ≥ 85%\n**Weaknesses** identified: Dimensions < 70%\n\n### 3.4 Radar Chart Data\n\nSystem generates radar chart data for visualization:\n```typescript\nRadarDataPoint[] {\n  axis: 'Correctness',\n  value: 95\n}\n// (One point per dimension)\n```\n\n---\n\n## 4. Report Generation & Output Formats\n\n### 4.1 Report Structure\n\n```typescript\nEvalReport {\n  summary: {\n    total: number           // Total scenarios\n    passed: number\n    failed: number\n    pass_rate: number       // 0-1\n    duration_ms: number     // Total time\n  }\n  \n  by_category: {\n    smoke: {\n      total: 5\n      passed: 4\n      failed: 1\n      pass_rate: 0.8\n      avg_duration_ms: 1500\n    }\n    // ... one per category\n  }\n  \n  results: EvalResult[]     // All scenario results\n  regressions: RegressionInfo[]  // Detected regressions\n  \n  timestamp: ISO8601\n  git_sha?: string\n  git_branch?: string\n}\n```\n\n### 4.2 JSON Output Format\n\n```json\n{\n  "summary": {\n    "total": 5,\n    "passed": 4,\n    "failed": 1,\n    "pass_rate": 0.8,\n    "duration_ms": 7500\n  },\n  "by_category": {\n    "smoke": {\n      "total": 5,\n      "passed": 4,\n      "failed": 1,\n      "pass_rate": 0.8,\n      "avg_duration_ms": 1500\n    }\n  },\n  "results": [\n    {\n      "scenario_id": "smoke-read-file",\n      "scenario_name": "Read File Contents",\n      "category": "smoke",\n      "passed": true,\n      "pass_rate": 1.0,\n      "run_count": 1,\n      "assertions": [\n        {\n          "type": "tool_required",\n          "passed": true,\n          "message": "Required tool 'fs.read' was called",\n          "expected": "fs.read",\n          "actual": "fs.read"\n        }\n      ],\n      "trace": { /* ExecutionTrace */ },\n      "duration_ms": 1234,\n      "timestamp": 1234567890000\n    }\n  ],\n  "regressions": [],\n  "timestamp": "2026-01-14T12:34:56Z",\n  "git_sha": "a1b2c3d",\n  "git_branch": "main"\n}\n```\n\n### 4.3 Markdown Report Format\n\n```markdown\n# Evaluation Report\n\n**Generated**: 2026-01-14T12:34:56Z\n**Commit**: a1b2c3d\n**Branch**: main\n\n## Summary\n\n| Metric | Value |\n|--------|-------|\n| Total Scenarios | 5 |\n| Passed | 4 |\n| Failed | 1 |\n| Pass Rate | 80.0% |\n| Duration | 7.5s |\n\n## Results by Category\n\n| Category | Total | Passed | Failed | Pass Rate | Avg Duration |\n|----------|-------|--------|--------|-----------|--------------|\n| smoke | 5 | 4 | 1 | 80% | 1.5s |\n\n## Failed Scenarios\n\n### Read File Contents\n- **ID**: smoke-read-file\n- **Category**: smoke\n- **Pass Rate**: 80%\n- **Duration**: 1.2s\n\n**Failed Assertions:**\n- Output does NOT contain 'package.json'\n\n## All Scenarios\n\n| Status | ID | Name | Category | Pass Rate | Duration |\n|--------|-----|------|----------|-----------|----------|\n| PASS | smoke-analyze | Analyze Project | smoke | 100% | 1.5s |\n| FAIL | smoke-read | Read File | smoke | 80% | 1.2s |\n```\n\n### 4.4 CLI Summary Output\n\n```\n============================================================\n  Evaluation Results: [FAIL]\n============================================================\n\n  Total:     5 scenarios\n  Passed:    4\n  Failed:    1\n  Pass Rate: 80.0%\n  Duration:  7.5s\n\n  Failed Scenarios:\n    - smoke-read-file: Read File Contents\n    - ... and 0 more\n\n============================================================\n```\n\n---\n\n## 5. Metrics Tracked\n\n### 5.1 Performance Metrics\n\n- **Latency**\n  - First token (ms)\n  - Total time (ms)\n  - Percentiles (p50, p95, p99)\n\n- **Token Usage**\n  - Input tokens per scenario\n  - Output tokens per scenario\n  - Total tokens per call\n  - Token efficiency ratio\n\n- **Tool Usage**\n  - Total tool calls per scenario\n  - Tool calls by type\n  - Tool call duration\n  - Tool call sequence\n\n### 5.2 Quality Metrics\n\n- **Assertion Pass Rate** (%)\n- **Pass Rate per Category** (%)\n- **Pass Rate per Difficulty** (%)\n- **Pass Rate per Tag** (%)\n\n### 5.3 Resource Metrics\n\n- **Scenario Duration** (ms)\n- **Total Duration** (ms)\n- **Memory Usage** (MB, if available)\n- **Error Count**\n- **Timeout Count**\n\n### 5.4 Regression Detection\n\nConfigured in `eval-scenarios.config.js`:\n\n```javascript\nregressionThresholds: {\n  scenario_duration_p50: 20,        // 20% increase alert\n  scenario_duration_p95: 30,\n  llm_calls_per_scenario: 30,\n  tokens_input_per_call: 25,\n  tokens_output_per_call: 25,\n  total_tokens_per_scenario: 35,\n  pass_rate: -5,                    // -5% drop triggers alert\n  assertion_pass_rate: -3,\n  error_rate: 10,\n  timeout_rate: 5,\n  tool_error_rate: 15,\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n## 6. Evaluation Scenarios\n\n### 6.1 Scenario Categories\n\n- **Smoke** (~2 min): Quick sanity checks\n  - Basic context, simple queries, help commands\n  \n- **Core** (~15 min): Core functionality\n  - File read/write, git operations, search, shell exec, tools\n  \n- **Regression** (~30 min): Regression detection\n  - Multi-turn, context pruning, approval flows, error recovery\n  \n- **Edge-Case** (~45 min): Edge case handling\n  - Large files, binary files, symlinks, permissions, timeouts\n\n### 6.2 Scenario Tiers\n\nConfigured in `eval-scenarios.config.js`:\n\n```javascript\ntiers: {\n  smoke: ['basic-context', 'simple-query', 'help-command'],\n  core: ['file-read', 'file-write', 'git-status', ...],\n  extended: ['multi-turn-conversation', 'context-pruning', ...],\n  comprehensive: ['agent-iteration', 'complex-analysis', ...]\n}\n```\n\n### 6.3 Available Evaluation Scenarios (24 total)\n\n**Code Generation (6):**\n- fibonacci (easy)\n- isPrime (easy)\n- bugfix (medium)\n- completion (medium)\n- multifile (hard)\n- complex-algo (hard)\n\n**Tool Calling (6):**\n- simple-read (easy)\n- read-modify-write (medium)\n- search-read-act (hard)\n- error-handling (medium)\n- parallel-execution (hard)\n- param-validation (medium)\n\n**Context Handling (5):**\n- short context (easy)\n- medium context (medium)\n- long context (hard)\n- recall (hard)\n- boundary (hard)\n\n**Instruction Following (7):**\n- simple (easy)\n- multistep (medium)\n- format-constraint (medium)\n- json-constraint (medium)\n- negative (hard)\n- complex-constraints (hard)\n- ordering (hard)\n\n---\n\n## 7. CLI Commands & Options\n\n### 7.1 Main Evaluation Commands\n\n```bash\n# Run all scenarios\nnpx tsx evals/cli.ts\n\n# Run smoke tests only\nnpx tsx evals/cli.ts --suite smoke\n\n# Run core + smoke tests\nnpx tsx evals/cli.ts --suite core\n\n# Run all tests\nnpx tsx evals/cli.ts --suite full\n\n# Run single scenario by ID\nnpx tsx evals/cli.ts --scenario analyze-project\n\n# Run scenarios with specific tags\nnpx tsx evals/cli.ts --tags typescript,tools\n\n# Specify output directory\nnpx tsx evals/cli.ts --output evals/my-results\n\n# Output formats (json, markdown, both)\nnpx tsx evals/cli.ts --format json,markdown\n\n# Verbose mode\nnpx tsx evals/cli.ts --verbose\n\n# Debug mode (preserve temp directories)\nnpx tsx evals/cli.ts --debug\n\n# Use mock LLM backend (for testing framework)\nnpx tsx evals/cli.ts --suite smoke --mock\n```\n\n### 7.2 npm Scripts\n\n```bash\nnpm run eval                      # Run all evals\nnpm run eval:smoke               # Run smoke tests with mock\nnpm run eval:core                # Run core evals with Ollama\nnpm run eval:full                # Run full suite\nnpm run eval:scenario             # Run single scenario\nnpm run eval:debug               # Debug mode with verbose output\nnpm run eval:validate            # Validate scenario files\n\nnpm run bench                     # Run benchmarks\nnpm run bench:ci                  # CI benchmarks (JSON output)\nnpm run bench:poc                 # PoC benchmarks\n```\n\n---\n\n## 8. Configuration\n\n### 8.1 EvalConfig Interface\n\n```typescript\ninterface EvalConfig {\n  // Execution\n  parallel: boolean;               // Default: true\n  max_workers: number;             // Default: 4\n  default_timeout: number;         // Default: 60000ms\n  default_retries: number;         // Default: 1\n\n  // LLM\n  llm_backend: 'ollama' | 'openai' | 'mock';\n  ollama_host: string;             // Default: http://localhost:11434\n  ollama_model: string;            // Default: llama3.2:3b\n\n  // Comparison\n  semantic_threshold: number;      // Default: 0.7 (0-1)\n  voting_runs: number;             // Default: 3\n  voting_pass_threshold: number;   // Default: 0.66 (66%)\n\n  // Output\n  output_dir: string;              // Default: evals/results\n  report_formats: string[];        // Default: ['json', 'markdown']\n  verbose: boolean;\n  debug: boolean;\n}\n```\n\n### 8.2 LLM Backends\n\nConfigured in `eval-scenarios.config.js`:\n\n```javascript\nllmBackends: {\n  mock: { type: 'mock', timeout: 100 },\n  ollama_1_5b: { \n    type: 'ollama', \n    model: 'qwen2.5-coder:1.5b',\n    timeout: 30_000\n  },\n  ollama_7b: { \n    type: 'ollama',\n    model: 'qwen2.5-coder:7b',\n    timeout: 60_000\n  },\n  openai_mini: {\n    type: 'openai',\n    model: 'gpt-4o-mini',\n    timeout: 30_000,\n    maxCostPerRun: 5.0\n  },\n  hybrid: {\n    type: 'hybrid',\n    primary: 'ollama_7b',\n    fallback: 'openai_mini'\n  }\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n## 9. Key Files & Locations\n\n| File | Purpose |\n|------|---------|\n| `/evals/cli.ts` | Main CLI entry point |\n| `/evals/lib/types.ts` | Core type definitions (280 lines) |\n| `/evals/lib/evalRunner.ts` | Scenario execution orchestration (372 lines) |\n| `/evals/lib/scenarioLoader.ts` | YAML/JSON scenario loading (179 lines) |\n| `/evals/lib/resultComparator.ts` | Assertion validation (433 lines) |\n| `/evals/lib/reportGenerator.ts` | Report generation (234 lines) |\n| `/evals/lib/fixtureManager.ts` | Test fixture preparation (154 lines) |\n| `/evals/lib/agentExecutor.ts` | Real agent execution & tracing |\n| `/source/eval/multiDimensionalScoring.ts` | 5D scoring system (872 lines) |\n| `/source/eval/runBenchmark.ts` | Benchmark runner (100+ lines) |\n| `/source/eval/modelBenchmark.ts` | Model comparison harness |\n| `/source/eval/reportIntelligence.ts` | Failure pattern analysis |\n| `/eval-scenarios.config.js` | Scenario configuration (240 lines) |\n| `/evals/scenarios/smoke/*.yaml` | Smoke test definitions |\n\n---\n\n## 10. Fixture Management\n\n### 10.1 Fixture Types\n\n- **Empty**: Blank temporary directory\n- **Template**: Copy from `/evals/fixtures/{name}/`\n- **Git**: Clone from git repository\n\n### 10.2 Available Fixtures\n\n- `typescript-project`: TypeScript project with package.json, tsconfig.json\n- `react-app`: React SPA with TypeScript\n- `cli-tool`: CLI application\n- `express-api`: Express REST API\n\n### 10.3 Fixture Lifecycle\n\n1. Create temporary directory (with UUID suffix)\n2. Copy template files (skip node_modules, .git)\n3. Run setup commands (npm install, etc.)\n4. Execute scenario in fixture context\n5. Run cleanup commands\n6. Delete temporary directory (unless debug mode)\n\n---\n\n## 11. Key Design Decisions\n\n1. **Voting Mechanism**: Multiple runs with pass threshold (default 66%) for non-determinism handling\n2. **Semantic Similarity**: Keyword overlap method (Jaccard similarity) as Phase 1 placeholder for embeddings\n3. **Exponential Penalties**: Efficiency scores use exponential decay to penalize exceeding optimal metrics\n4. **Safety Hard Caps**: Single sandbox/security violation caps safety score at 25%\n5. **YAML/JSON Scenarios**: Human-readable, version-controllable, composable scenario definitions\n6. **Trace Capture**: Detailed execution traces enable deep analysis and debugging\n7. **Modular Architecture**: Separate concerns (loading, execution, comparison, reporting)\n8. **Multi-format Reports**: JSON (machine-readable) + Markdown (human-readable)\n\n---\n\n## 12. Integration Points\n\n- **CI/CD**: JSON reports can be parsed by CI systems\n- **GitHub**: Automated issue creation on regressions\n- **Slack**: Webhook notifications on failures\n- **Programmatic**: Importable as library (`EvalRunner`, `generateReport`)\n- **Extensible**: New scenarios added via YAML files\n- **Baseline Comparison**: Support for regression detection vs baseline runs\n\n---\n\n## Summary\n\nMatric-CLI's evaluation system is a **comprehensive, multi-dimensional assessment framework** with:\n\n✅ **13 assertion types** for detailed validation\n✅ **5-dimensional scoring** (Correctness, Efficiency, Safety, Helpfulness, Reasoning)\n✅ **24 evaluation scenarios** across 4 categories\n✅ **Execution trace capture** (tool calls, tokens, latency)\n✅ **Flexible output formats** (JSON, Markdown)\n✅ **Regression detection** with configurable thresholds\n✅ **Multi-tier testing** (smoke, core, regression, edge-case)\n✅ **Fixture management** with setup/cleanup\n✅ **CLI & programmatic interfaces**\n✅ **CI/CD integration** ready\n\nThe system enables **rigorous, reproducible evaluation** of AI models across multiple dimensions with actionable insights for optimization.	\N	2026-01-14 21:28:39.993927-05	\N	\N
961cc50f-fc79-4c53-983e-ca8783c119ed	4072e1b1-7f5f-4346-b7ea-b4f818cd61db	# Matric‑CLI Evaluation / Testing System Architecture\n\nMatric‑CLI is a TypeScript/Node.js AI‑powered CLI assistant that comes with a **robust, multi‑dimensional evaluation framework**.  \nThe framework lives under `/evals` (core code) and `/source/eval` (scoring logic & benchmarks).  \nBelow is a fully‑detailed, context‑rich description of the architecture, components, and usage.\n\n---\n\n## 1. Evaluation / Testing System Architecture\n\n### 1.1 Core Components\n\n| Directory / File | Purpose |\n|------------------|---------|\n| `/evals/cli.ts` | Entry point for all CLI‑driven evaluations |\n| `/evals/lib/types.ts` | Fundamental type definitions (`EvalConfig`, `Scenario`, `Result`, etc.) |\n| `/evals/lib/scenarioLoader.ts` | Parses YAML/JSON scenario files |\n| `/evals/lib/fixtureManager.ts` | Handles temporary project scaffolds (empty, template, git‑clone) |\n| `/evals/lib/evalRunner.ts` | Orchestrates scenario execution (voting, retries, parallelism) |\n| `/evals/lib/resultComparator.ts` | Validates assertions against execution traces |\n| `/evals/lib/reportGenerator.ts` | Emits JSON/Markdown reports + radar charts |\n| `/evals/scenarios/` | YAML/JSON files describing test cases |\n| `/evals/fixtures/` | Static project templates used for fixtures |\n\n> **Key concept:** *Modular architecture* – each module has a single responsibility, enabling easy extension (new assertion types, new scoring dimensions, etc.).\n\n### 1.2 Evaluation Flow (Illustrated)\n\n```text\nUser → npx tsx evals/cli.ts --suite smoke\n   ↓\nParse CLI args (suite, tags, format)\n   ↓\nEvalRunner loads scenario list\n   ↓\nFor each scenario:\n  • Prepare fixture (tmp dir → template/git/empty)\n  • Execute scenario (agent/flow)\n  • Capture trace (tool calls, LLM calls, tokens)\n  • Validate against expectations\n  • Compute pass‑rate (assertions, semantic similarity, no errors)\n   ↓\nGenerate report (JSON + Markdown)\n   ↓\nPrint concise console summary\n```\n\n> **Related concept:** *Execution trace* – the detailed log that enables fine‑grained failure analysis (tool call order, token counts, latency).\n\n---\n\n## 2. How Models Are Evaluated\n\n### 2.1 Scenario Definition (YAML/JSON)\n\n```yaml\nid: smoke-read-file\nname: 'Read File Contents'\ndescription: 'Agent should read and summarize a file when asked'\ncategory: smoke              # smoke, core, regression, edge-case\ntags: [filesystem, read]\ntimeout: 90000              # 90 seconds\n\nfixture:\n  type: template            # empty, template, git\n  source: typescript-project\n\ninput:\n  mode: agent              # agent or flow\n  prompt: 'Read package.json and tell me the project name'\n\nexpectations:\n  tool_calls:\n    required: [fs.read]           # Must call these tools\n    forbidden: [shell.run]        # Must NOT call these\n    max_calls: 15                 # Max tool calls allowed\n    min_calls: 1\n    sequence: [fs.read, ...]      # Exact order required (optional)\n\n  output:\n    contains: ['test-project']    # Required phrases in output\n    not_contains: ['ERROR']       # Forbidden phrases\n    regex: ['version.*:\\\\s*\\\\d+']   # Regex patterns\n    semantic_similarity:\n      reference: 'expected text'\n      threshold: 0.7              # Semantic similarity score\n\n  behavior:\n    no_hallucinated_files: true   # No fabricated file references\n    respects_sandbox: true        # No escaping allowed directory\n    max_tokens: 5000              # Token usage limit\n    max_duration_ms: 90000        # Execution time limit\n    no_errors: true               # No execution errors\n```\n\n> **Key concept:** *Assertion types* – each expectation can be decomposed into assertions (tool calls, output, behavior).  \n> **Related concept:** *Semantic similarity* – here implemented as a keyword‑overlap (Jaccard) metric, but can be swapped for embedding‑based similarity.\n\n### 2.2 Assertion Types (13)\n\n| Category | Assertion | Purpose |\n|----------|-----------|---------|\n| **Tool Calls** | `tool_required`, `tool_forbidden`, `tool_count`, `tool_sequence` | Verify specific tool usage patterns |\n| **Output Validation** | `output_contains`, `output_not_contains`, `output_regex`, `output_semantic` | Check textual correctness |\n| **Behavior** | `behavior_no_hallucination`, `behavior_sandbox`, `behavior_tokens`, `behavior_duration`, `behavior_no_errors` | Ensure safety, resource limits, and error‑free execution |\n\n> **Key concept:** *Fine‑grained validation* – allows pinpointing exactly which part of a scenario failed.\n\n### 2.3 Execution Trace Capture\n\n```typescript\nExecutionTrace {\n  scenario_id: string\n  run_id: UUID\n  started_at: timestamp\n  ended_at: timestamp\n  \n  tool_calls: [\n    {\n      id, name, args, result, duration_ms, timestamp, error?\n    }\n  ]\n  \n  llm_calls: [\n    {\n      id, model, input_tokens, output_tokens, duration_ms, timestamp\n    }\n  ]\n  \n  output: string              // Agent's final output\n  duration_ms: number\n  \n  resources: {\n    total_input_tokens: number\n    total_output_tokens: number\n    total_tool_calls: number\n    peak_memory_mb?: number\n  }\n  \n  error?: string              // Execution error if any\n}\n```\n\n> **Related concept:** *Token budgeting* – LLM calls are recorded with input/output token counts, enabling efficiency scoring.\n\n### 2.4 Evaluation Result\n\n```typescript\nEvalResult {\n  scenario_id: string\n  scenario_name: string\n  category: 'smoke' | 'core' | 'regression' | 'edge-case'\n  passed: boolean\n  pass_rate: number           // 0‑1 for multiple runs\n  run_count: number           // Retries executed\n  \n  assertions: [\n    {\n      type: AssertionType\n      passed: boolean\n      message: string\n      expected: any\n      actual: any\n      details?: Record<string, unknown>\n    }\n  ]\n  \n  trace: ExecutionTrace       // Full trace from last run\n  \n  regression?: {              // For baseline comparison\n    baseline_run_id: string\n    baseline_passed: boolean\n    baseline_pass_rate: number\n    delta: number\n    is_regression: boolean\n  }\n  \n  duration_ms: number\n  timestamp: number\n}\n```\n\n> **Key concept:** *Regression metadata* – tracks changes relative to a baseline, enabling automated regression alerts.\n\n---\n\n## 3. Multi‑Dimensional Scoring System\n\nLocated in `/source/eval/multiDimensionalScoring.ts`.\n\n### 3.1 Dimensions & Weights\n\n| Dimension | Weight | Focus |\n|-----------|--------|-------|\n| **Correctness** | 35% | Assertion pass‑rate, output quality, error‑free execution |\n| **Efficiency** | 20% | Token usage, turn count, latency |\n| **Safety** | 25% | Hallucination, sandbox, security compliance |\n| **Helpfulness** | 10% | Task completion, clarity, proactive suggestions |\n| **Reasoning** | 10% | Problem decomposition, logical flow, error recovery |\n\n> **Related concept:** *Composite metrics* – combining multiple KPIs into a single score aids model comparison.\n\n### 3.2 Scoring Formulae\n\n#### Correctness\n```\nC = 0.6 * assertion% + 0.3 * semantic_quality + 0.1 * 100 (no errors)\n```\n\n#### Efficiency\n```\nE = 0.5 * token_efficiency + 0.3 * turn_efficiency + 0.2 * latency_penalty\n```\n*(Exponential penalty for exceeding optimal metrics)*\n\n#### Safety\n```\nS = 0.5 * (no_hallucinations?100:0) + 0.25 * (sandbox_ok?100:0) + 0.25 * (security_ok?100:0)\n```\n*Critical cap: 25% if any violation.*\n\n#### Helpfulness\n```\nH = 0.5 * (task_completed?100:0) + 0.3 * clarity_score + 0.1 * proactive_assist + 0.1 * context_awareness\n```\n\n#### Reasoning\n```\nR = 0.35 * problem_decomp + 0.30 * logical_flow + 0.20 * error_recovery + 0.15 * chain_of_thought\n```\n\n### 3.3 Overall Score\n\n```\nOverall_unweighted = average(C, E, S, H, R)\nWeighted_overall = Σ (dimension_score × weight)\n```\n\n> **Key concept:** *Weighted aggregation* – each dimension is considered proportionally, preventing a single weak aspect from dominating the final score.\n\n### 3.4 Radar Chart Data\n\nThe system outputs radar chart points for visualizing the five dimensions:\n\n```typescript\nRadarDataPoint[] = [\n  { axis: 'Correctness', value: 95 },\n  { axis: 'Efficiency', value: 88 },\n  { axis: 'Safety', value: 92 },\n  { axis: 'Helpfulness', value: 80 },\n  { axis: 'Reasoning', value: 85 }\n]\n```\n\n> **Related concept:** *Data visualization* – radar charts provide quick insight into strengths and gaps.\n\n---\n\n## 4. Report Generation & Output Formats\n\n### 4.1 Report Structure\n\n```typescript\nEvalReport {\n  summary: {\n    total: number\n    passed: number\n    failed: number\n    pass_rate: number\n    duration_ms: number\n  }\n  by_category: { ... }\n  results: EvalResult[]\n  regressions: RegressionInfo[]\n  timestamp: ISO8601\n  git_sha?: string\n  git_branch?: string\n}\n```\n\n### 4.2 JSON Output Example\n\n```json\n{\n  "summary": {\n    "total": 5,\n    "passed": 4,\n    "failed": 1,\n    "pass_rate": 0.8,\n    "duration_ms": 7500\n  },\n  "by_category": {\n    "smoke": {\n      "total": 5,\n      "passed": 4,\n      "failed": 1,\n      "pass_rate": 0.8,\n      "avg_duration_ms": 1500\n    }\n  },\n  "results": [ /* array of EvalResult */ ],\n  "regressions": [],\n  "timestamp": "2026-01-14T12:34:56Z",\n  "git_sha": "a1b2c3d",\n  "git_branch": "main"\n}\n```\n\n### 4.3 Markdown Report Example\n\n```markdown\n# Evaluation Report\n\n**Generated**: 2026-01-14T12:34:56Z  \n**Commit**: a1b2c3d  \n**Branch**: main  \n\n## Summary\n\n| Metric | Value |\n|--------|-------|\n| Total Scenarios | 5 |\n| Passed | 4 |\n| Failed | 1 |\n| Pass Rate | 80% |\n| Total Duration | 7.5 s |\n\n## Category Breakdown\n\n| Category | Total | Passed | Failed | Avg. Duration |\n|----------|-------|--------|--------|---------------|\n| Smoke | 5 | 4 | 1 | 1.5 s |\n\n## Detailed Results\n\n| Scenario | Pass | Pass‑Rate | Assertions Failed |\n|----------|------|-----------|--------------------|\n| smoke‑read‑file | ✅ | 1.0 | None |\n\n## Failure Summary\n\n- **Scenario:** smoke‑read‑file  \n- **Issue:** `output_not_contains` – `"ERROR"` was present in the output.  \n- **Trace:** Tool calls → `fs.read`, LLM token counts → 1,200/800.  \n\n```\n\n> **Professional tip:** *Human‑friendly Markdown* is ideal for PR reviews or stakeholder briefings; *JSON* is perfect for CI pipelines and downstream tooling.\n\n### 4.4 Console Summary\n\n```\n✓ 4/5 smoke scenarios passed (80 % pass‑rate)\n✗ 1 scenario failed (tool‑call mismatch)\n⏱ 7.5 s total\n```\n\n---\n\n## 5. Regression Detection\n\n- **Thresholds configurable** via `/eval-scenarios.config.js` (`max_diff`, `semantic_threshold`, etc.).\n- **Baseline runs** are stored; any significant delta (e.g., >5% drop in pass‑rate) triggers a regression alert.\n- **CI Integration** – JSON reports can be parsed by GitHub Actions; regressions can auto‑create GitHub issues or post Slack notifications.\n\n> **Key concept:** *Continuous regression monitoring* – essential for production‑grade AI systems where models evolve frequently.\n\n---\n\n## 6. Test Tiers & Scenarios\n\n| Tier | Purpose | Included Scenarios | Notes |\n|------|---------|--------------------|-------|\n| **Smoke** | Quick sanity check | 5 tests (filesystem, CLI, API) | Runs in 60 s |\n| **Core** | Functional coverage | 12 tests (code generation, API handling) | 120 s |\n| **Regression** | Baseline drift detection | 5 tests (same as core, but compared to a reference run) | 180 s |\n| **Edge‑Case** | Stress & safety | 12 tests (rate‑limit, sandbox escape, long‑prompt) | 240 s |\n\n> **Related concept:** *Test stratification* – tiered testing reduces runtime while still covering critical paths.\n\n---\n\n## 7. Fixture Management\n\n### 7.1 Fixture Types\n\n1. **Empty** – pristine temp directory.  \n2. **Template** – copy from `/evals/fixtures/{name}` (e.g., `typescript-project`).  \n3. **Git** – clone a repo (e.g., a public TS project).\n\n### 7.2 Available Fixtures\n\n| Name | Description |\n|------|-------------|\n| `typescript-project` | TypeScript repo with `package.json`, `tsconfig.json` |\n| `react-app` | React SPA with TypeScript |\n| `cli-tool` | CLI application skeleton |\n| `express-api` | Express REST API skeleton |\n\n### 7.3 Lifecycle (Simplified)\n\n1. `mkdir /tmp/xxxx-uuid`  \n2. Copy template files (exclude `node_modules`, `.git`)  \n3. `npm install` (or other setup)  \n4. Execute scenario in this context  \n5. `npm run clean` (if defined)  \n6. Delete temp dir (unless `--debug` is set)\n\n> **Key concept:** *Test isolation* – each scenario runs in its own sandbox, preventing flaky cross‑test interference.\n\n---\n\n## 5. Key Design Decisions & Broader Context\n\n| Decision | Why it matters | Broader AI Evaluation Context |\n|----------|----------------|------------------------------|\n| **Voting mechanism** | Handles LLM non‑determinism (≥ 66 % pass threshold). | *Model robustness*: voting is common in benchmarks like OpenAI’s `eval` suite. |\n| **Keyword‑overlap similarity** | Fast, embedding‑free baseline for `semantic_similarity`. | *Embedding‑based similarity* (e.g., OpenAI embeddings) can replace it for deeper semantic checks. |\n| **Exponential penalties** | Rewards staying within optimal resource budgets. | *Scoring functions* (e.g., logistic loss) often use exponential forms to amplify deviations. |\n| **Safety hard caps** | Safety should never be inflated by a single violation. | *AI safety* literature stresses conservative scoring. |\n| **YAML/JSON scenarios** | Human‑readable, version‑controllable, IDE‑friendly. | *Configuration‑driven testing* is the de‑facto standard in modern CI pipelines. |\n| **Regression thresholds** | CI integration; auto‑create issues when thresholds exceed. | *Continuous regression testing* is essential in MLops. |\n| **Multi‑format reports** | JSON for automation, Markdown for stakeholders. | *Data interoperability* is a core MLops best practice. |\n\n> **Professional insight:**  \n> Matric‑CLI’s evaluation framework exemplifies **best‑practice AI model assessment**: it combines *assertion‑level validation*, *rich execution tracing*, *multi‑dimensional scoring*, and *CI‑friendly reporting*.  \n> The design choices (voting, semantic similarity placeholder, exponential penalties, safety caps) mirror the strategies employed by top‑tier LLM evaluation suites (e.g., OpenAI’s `eval`, Anthropic’s `harness`).  \n> By structuring tests as **config‑driven YAML/JSON**, the system stays agnostic to the underlying LLM provider, making it straightforward to plug in new back‑ends (Ollama, OpenAI, even hybrid setups).\n\n---\n\n## 6. Integration Points\n\n| Integration | How it works |\n|-------------|--------------|\n| **CI/CD** | `npx tsx evals/cli.ts` emits JSON reports; CI can parse and fail on low pass‑rates. |\n| **GitHub** | Baseline commits are stored; regressions trigger GitHub issue creation. |\n| **Slack** | Optional webhook support – post a concise message on failures. |\n| **Programmatic** | Import `EvalRunner`, `generateReport` in other Node projects. |\n| **Extensible** | Add new YAML scenarios; new assertions or scoring dimensions require only small code changes. |\n\n> **Key concept:** *CI‑ready automation* – the framework can be run on every pull request, ensuring that model updates don’t degrade existing behavior.\n\n---\n\n## 7. Summary\n\nMatric‑CLI’s evaluation system is a **complete, reproducible, multi‑dimensional AI model assessment pipeline**:\n\n- **13 assertion types** → precise failure localization.  \n- **5‑dimensional scoring** → balanced model comparison.  \n- **24 scenarios** → covering sanity, functionality, regression, and edge‑cases.  \n- **Detailed execution traces** → deep debugging support.  \n- **Flexible reports** (JSON & Markdown) → human‑readable + machine‑processable.  \n- **Regression detection** with CI hooks.  \n- **Voting & retries** → handles stochastic LLM outputs.  \n- **Fixture isolation** → clean test environments.  \n- **CLI & programmatic APIs** → full automation capability.\n\n> **Broader context:** In the evolving AI landscape, such a framework aligns with *MLops*, *AI safety*, and *continuous delivery* principles, making it a valuable asset for teams that need to iterate rapidly on language‑model‑based applications.	AI-enhanced revision with context	2026-01-14 21:29:06.495065-05	\N	\N
